WEBVTT

00:04.091 --> 00:05.048
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:05.092 --> 00:06.267
Oh, my God.

00:06.310 --> 00:07.659
Is this why you ended things
with me?

00:07.703 --> 00:09.139
Ended things with you?

00:09.183 --> 00:11.489
Did you go out
with my daughter?

00:11.533 --> 00:13.491
- There are several tumors.
- Is it malignant?

00:13.535 --> 00:16.016
We'll send the tissue
for pathology.

00:16.059 --> 00:17.408
Is that your wedding ring?

00:17.452 --> 00:19.062
The Chief of ED
at Andrew's hospital

00:19.106 --> 00:20.324
is retiring.

00:20.368 --> 00:21.804
Andrew wants
to put me up for the job.

00:21.847 --> 00:24.589
It's been nice, you know,
having my old rival back.

00:24.633 --> 00:27.592
But, uh, you gotta do
what's right for you.

00:27.636 --> 00:29.768
Is my 5:30 Thursday
still available?

00:29.812 --> 00:32.336
I'm trying to lighten
my patient load.

00:32.380 --> 00:34.860
I deserve a little more
of an explanation.

00:34.904 --> 00:37.080
After 20 years, I don't--
I don't make the cut?

00:37.124 --> 00:40.736
I have developed feelings
for you, Daniel.

00:43.217 --> 00:45.132
Thank you.

00:45.175 --> 00:47.525
- Oh, hi.
- Hey, there.

00:47.569 --> 00:48.961
- I was just on my--
- What are you doing?

00:49.005 --> 00:50.354
You go.

00:50.398 --> 00:52.356
I'm on my way up
to Medical Records.

00:52.400 --> 00:54.010
Need to sign a few charts.

00:54.054 --> 00:55.316
Nice to see you.

00:55.359 --> 00:56.882
Have a good day.

00:56.926 --> 01:00.886
<i>[pensive music]</i>

01:00.930 --> 01:02.540
Hey. Hey, Lonnie?

01:04.325 --> 01:05.587
Look, I accept the fact

01:05.630 --> 01:06.892
that you can't
treat me anymore,

01:06.936 --> 01:08.851
and I--I respect that.

01:08.894 --> 01:10.287
But, I--it's also--

01:10.331 --> 01:12.507
it's important
for me to tell you

01:12.550 --> 01:16.076
that--that the--
the work we did together?

01:16.119 --> 01:19.514
Um, you really helped me.
A lot.

01:20.732 --> 01:23.083
And I wanted
to thank you for it.

01:23.126 --> 01:24.258
I appreciate that, Dan.

01:25.607 --> 01:27.174
Okay, take care.

01:30.177 --> 01:31.482
Hey.

01:34.268 --> 01:37.227
Daniel?
- Hey.

01:37.271 --> 01:39.577
You seeing her
in person again, huh?

01:39.621 --> 01:42.276
No, you know,
she, um--she dumped me.

01:42.319 --> 01:43.842
She's been your therapist
for years.

01:43.886 --> 01:45.627
What happened?

01:45.670 --> 01:47.585
She developed feelings
for me.

01:47.629 --> 01:50.893
- Feelings?
- Yeah, romantic feelings, man.

01:50.936 --> 01:52.155
She give you a referral?

01:52.199 --> 01:53.809
Well, sure, but I mean,
you know,

01:53.852 --> 01:57.247
changing shrinks is not
exactly like changing sneakers.

01:57.291 --> 01:59.423
You know?
- True, true.

01:59.467 --> 02:01.860
Are you okay?
- [sighs] Yeah.

02:03.732 --> 02:05.342
How're you doing?

02:05.386 --> 02:08.432
You know, I think
I left my phone in the car.

02:08.476 --> 02:10.652
Look, I'm going
to be here all day,

02:10.695 --> 02:12.306
so if you want
to talk some more...

02:12.349 --> 02:13.698
I'm fine.

02:13.742 --> 02:15.787
But thank you,
and I'll see you around.

02:15.831 --> 02:17.180
All right.

02:20.836 --> 02:23.273
You're going to T2.
Thank you.

02:23.317 --> 02:26.624
Hey, biopsy results
come back yet?

02:26.668 --> 02:28.322
Not yet,
but the lab promises

02:28.365 --> 02:31.629
that sometime today.
[sighs]

02:31.673 --> 02:33.892
You know there's
a good chance it's benign.

02:33.936 --> 02:36.460
I'm not so sure.

02:36.504 --> 02:39.202
I had cancer before.
- Oh.

02:39.246 --> 02:40.595
It's just--

02:41.900 --> 02:44.381
You're afraid
your cancer's come back.

02:46.470 --> 02:48.907
breathing shakily]

02:51.780 --> 02:54.261
Chest sounds good.

02:54.304 --> 02:56.872
X-rays, a lot better.

02:56.915 --> 02:58.439
As long as he continues
to improve,

02:58.482 --> 03:00.092
I don't see any reason why
we can't discharge him.

03:00.136 --> 03:02.225
- Oh.
- It still hurts.

03:02.269 --> 03:05.315
Yeah, well, pneumonia's
no joke, D-man.

03:05.359 --> 03:06.403
Look, I'ma give your mom
some medicine

03:06.447 --> 03:08.275
to make you feel better, okay?

03:12.409 --> 03:14.281
Due to his pneumonia,

03:14.324 --> 03:15.325
it'll be a couple weeks
before he can

03:15.369 --> 03:18.023
go back on chemo.
- Okay.

03:18.067 --> 03:19.851
Any word from Terrell?

03:19.895 --> 03:21.244
No.

03:21.288 --> 03:23.812
And he's never stayed away
this long.

03:23.855 --> 03:24.856
This isn't like him.

03:28.164 --> 03:29.861
- Thank you.
- Sure.

03:31.950 --> 03:33.082
Morning, Ms. Goodwin.

03:33.125 --> 03:34.301
Dr. Shentu.

03:34.344 --> 03:36.216
Seems like the Med staff
is adapting well

03:36.259 --> 03:37.652
to our new guidelines.

03:37.695 --> 03:39.088
<i>Your</i> new guidelines.

03:39.131 --> 03:40.698
And you really think so?

03:40.742 --> 03:42.265
In any case,
I appreciate the cooperation.

03:42.309 --> 03:43.919
My God, look out!
[tires screeching]

03:47.879 --> 03:50.708
[panting]

03:50.752 --> 03:52.275
Please, help me!
- We got you.

03:52.319 --> 03:53.711
It's okay, it's okay.

03:53.755 --> 03:56.323
I need a 911
and the emergency response team

03:56.366 --> 03:57.889
out front, main entrance.

03:57.933 --> 04:02.067
Single vehicle crash,
driver responsive.

04:02.111 --> 04:04.809
The patient's car
hit a concrete barrier.

04:04.853 --> 04:06.289
The airbag deployed,

04:06.333 --> 04:07.986
but no visible signs of injury.

04:08.030 --> 04:09.074
Heart rate's steady.

04:09.118 --> 04:10.728
Having a lot
of generalized pain.

04:10.772 --> 04:12.469
Okay, everyone,
let's get ready.

04:12.513 --> 04:14.079
Got it? On my count.

04:14.123 --> 04:16.430
One, two, three.

04:16.473 --> 04:18.736
Okay, let's get a cannula
and IV in.

04:18.780 --> 04:20.303
Let's put her up on a monitor,
draw trauma labs.

04:20.347 --> 04:21.522
We need x-rays stat.

04:21.565 --> 04:22.871
- Yup.
- Dr. Shentu.

04:22.914 --> 04:25.917
<i>[tense music]</i>

04:25.961 --> 04:28.442
BP 95/65.

04:28.485 --> 04:30.531
Heart rate and sats
not picking up.

04:30.574 --> 04:32.359
Cycle it again.

04:33.447 --> 04:35.318
Clear.
[x-ray beeps]

04:36.972 --> 04:38.408
Chest is okay.

04:38.452 --> 04:40.628
No hemo or pneumothorax.
Mediastinum is normal.

04:40.671 --> 04:42.978
Ultrasound? Thank you.

04:44.980 --> 04:48.157
[ultrasound pulses]
Fast is negative.

04:48.200 --> 04:49.550
Got an ID.

04:49.593 --> 04:50.942
Name's Gia Lindahl.

04:50.986 --> 04:52.553
I can see
if there's a history.

04:52.596 --> 04:54.206
She's too distracted
to clear her C-spine.

04:54.250 --> 04:55.512
Let's keep
the collar on for now.

04:55.556 --> 04:57.297
Dr. Shentu, pupils?

04:57.340 --> 04:58.820
Yeah. Spare penlight?

05:03.520 --> 05:06.567
Pupils equal and reactive.
Little sluggish.

05:06.610 --> 05:08.351
Ms. Lindahl,
can you hear me?

05:08.395 --> 05:09.961
- [groans]
- Ms. Lindahl?

05:10.005 --> 05:11.528
GCS 12.

05:11.572 --> 05:12.790
She is a patient here.

05:12.834 --> 05:14.444
One of the first
we treated for COVID.

05:14.488 --> 05:16.490
Been back a few times
with long-haul symptoms.

05:16.533 --> 05:17.926
Give her 50 mics
of fentanyl.

05:17.969 --> 05:19.231
Let's get a pelvis x-ray,

05:19.275 --> 05:20.711
and let's send her up to CT
for a pan scan,

05:20.755 --> 05:22.147
and make sure we add
a tox to her blood and urine.

05:22.191 --> 05:23.323
Yep.

05:24.628 --> 05:27.196
Dr. Shentu, why don't
you see this through?

05:27.239 --> 05:28.893
Uh, certainly.

05:28.937 --> 05:30.939
And Dr. Taylor,
you run point.

05:30.982 --> 05:33.158
Doris, let's get the doctor
a pair of scrubs.

05:33.202 --> 05:34.638
Okay.

05:38.076 --> 05:39.991
Did you just assign
the compliance officer

05:40.035 --> 05:41.297
to a medical case?

05:41.341 --> 05:42.777
He's a critical care doctor

05:42.820 --> 05:44.474
who's credentialed at Med.

05:44.518 --> 05:46.607
He's a bureaucrat.
A suit.

05:46.650 --> 05:48.913
Nevertheless, I know
you'll be accommodating.

05:51.612 --> 05:52.830
Yeah, do me a favor,
keep me briefed

05:52.874 --> 05:55.180
on Dr. Shentu's
performance today.

05:55.224 --> 05:56.486
Sure.

05:56.530 --> 06:02.536
<i>â™ª</i>

06:06.409 --> 06:07.976
[sobs]
Oh, God.

06:08.019 --> 06:10.761
Why does my body
feel like it's on fire?

06:10.805 --> 06:12.197
Given everything we've seen,

06:12.241 --> 06:14.765
we think you have a condition
called fibromyalgia.

06:14.809 --> 06:16.506
Let's give her
another 50 of fentanyl.

06:16.550 --> 06:19.379
[groaning]

06:19.422 --> 06:20.815
Fibromyalgia?

06:20.858 --> 06:22.425
We've seen it
in long-haul COVID patients

06:22.469 --> 06:24.775
like yourself; there's
even a name, "Fibro-COVID."

06:24.819 --> 06:26.342
What causes it?

06:26.386 --> 06:28.344
We think it's due
to a problem in the way

06:28.388 --> 06:29.650
that the spinal cord
and the brain

06:29.693 --> 06:30.868
process pain signals.

06:30.912 --> 06:31.869
It's not life-threatening,
but it is--

06:31.913 --> 06:33.610
It's terrible.

06:33.654 --> 06:35.264
We need
a rheumatology consult,

06:35.307 --> 06:36.700
but for right now,
we're giving you

06:36.744 --> 06:38.006
more pain meds
so you can get some rest,

06:38.049 --> 06:38.963
all right?
- [groans]

06:39.007 --> 06:40.008
The good news, Gia?

06:40.051 --> 06:41.313
According to your scans,

06:41.357 --> 06:42.967
there were no serious injuries
with your crash.

06:43.011 --> 06:45.796
Oh, I'm so sorry.

06:45.840 --> 06:48.277
I should have never
driven myself.

06:48.320 --> 06:50.279
Dr. Taylor and I are
just happy you're safe

06:50.322 --> 06:51.759
and getting
the treatment you need.

06:58.243 --> 07:00.115
- Fibromyalgia.
- That's tough.

07:00.158 --> 07:01.290
Yeah.

07:01.333 --> 07:03.205
So how are you thinking
of treating her?

07:03.248 --> 07:05.425
There's data on patients
responding very well

07:05.468 --> 07:07.644
to Xyrem.
- Xyrem?

07:07.688 --> 07:11.866
As I recall, it's not
FDA-approved for fibromyalgia.

07:11.909 --> 07:13.128
- Right.
- Yeah, it's only approved

07:13.171 --> 07:14.695
for cataplexy and narcolepsy.

07:14.738 --> 07:16.000
We'd be using it off-label.

07:16.044 --> 07:17.306
And per your new mandates,

07:17.349 --> 07:20.222
our doctors can't prescribe
off-label meds

07:20.265 --> 07:21.876
without the patient's consent.

07:21.919 --> 07:23.921
And she's sedated now,
so she can't.

07:23.965 --> 07:25.880
Well, then as soon
as she wakes,

07:25.923 --> 07:27.490
we'll, uh, explain
the situation

07:27.534 --> 07:29.274
and ask for consent.

07:29.318 --> 07:31.973
Yeah, seems like
your only option.

07:36.368 --> 07:37.979
Dr. Scott!

07:38.022 --> 07:39.110
I understand we're doing
a transplant

07:39.154 --> 07:40.460
on a patient of yours.
- Yeah, yeah.

07:40.503 --> 07:42.418
I was glad you and Dr. Blake
got the case, man.

07:42.462 --> 07:43.637
Well, we're gonna take
good care of her, all right?

07:43.680 --> 07:45.116
Thank you.

07:45.160 --> 07:47.510
Dylan, I could use
an extra set of hands in here.

07:47.554 --> 07:49.947
30-something male. GCS 10.

07:49.991 --> 07:52.602
He was found passed out
in the street, inebriated.

07:52.646 --> 07:54.169
Right arm swollen
and discolored.

07:54.212 --> 07:56.084
- Terrell.
- You know him?

07:56.127 --> 07:57.564
Yeah, since we were kids.

07:57.607 --> 07:59.000
His son's a patient upstairs.

07:59.043 --> 08:00.610
Paramedics gave Narcan
in the field,

08:00.654 --> 08:01.916
but zero response.

08:01.959 --> 08:04.440
Still hypothermic.
- Terrell, you hear me?

08:04.484 --> 08:07.443
<i>[tense music]</i>

08:07.487 --> 08:08.575
<i>â™ª</i>

08:08.618 --> 08:10.533
Get away from me.

08:10.577 --> 08:11.665
Look, I'm just trying
to help, man.

08:11.708 --> 08:13.580
Not you.
[coughs]

08:13.623 --> 08:14.755
All right, he's rousable.

08:14.798 --> 08:16.408
Let's get this board
out of here.

08:16.452 --> 08:18.280
All right, on three.
One, two, three.

08:20.500 --> 08:21.718
Temp's 93.

08:21.762 --> 08:22.676
All right,
let's swap this out

08:22.719 --> 08:23.894
for one of our warmer blankets.

08:23.938 --> 08:26.810
And get him a liter
of NS on the warmer.

08:26.854 --> 08:28.595
Right arm's pretty tight.

08:28.638 --> 08:29.944
Hand's cold.

08:29.987 --> 08:31.902
Can't feel distal, ulnar,
or radial pulse.

08:31.946 --> 08:34.209
Compartment syndrome.

08:34.252 --> 08:35.515
Heart's a little tachy.

08:35.558 --> 08:38.648
Foley output.
5cc's of dark urine.

08:38.692 --> 08:40.781
Dead muscle's
causing him to go into rhabdo.

08:40.824 --> 08:42.086
Could be disaster
for his kidneys.

08:42.130 --> 08:43.479
He needs a fasciotomy.
Call Dr. Archer.

08:43.523 --> 08:45.307
On it.

08:45.350 --> 08:52.270
<i>â™ª</i>

08:52.314 --> 08:53.968
Hey.

08:54.011 --> 08:55.099
Any history you can share?

08:55.143 --> 08:57.145
Help us treat him?

08:57.188 --> 09:00.017
Terrell's kind of a mystery.

09:00.061 --> 09:02.542
When we were kids,
he was funny, smart.

09:02.585 --> 09:03.673
Then he drops out,

09:03.717 --> 09:05.980
starts hanging
with the wrong crowd.

09:06.023 --> 09:08.548
[sighs] After that,
things went downhill.

09:10.375 --> 09:12.290
It's tough to see
a life fall apart.

09:14.031 --> 09:15.772
He's been MIA for a while.

09:15.816 --> 09:17.339
I'm gonna go tell
his wife he's here.

09:17.382 --> 09:19.384
- Yeah.
- All right, thanks.

09:22.649 --> 09:24.651
Morning.

09:24.694 --> 09:26.827
Hey.

09:26.870 --> 09:28.568
Here you go.

09:28.611 --> 09:29.960
I hear that Stevie's
going back to Michigan

09:30.004 --> 09:31.005
to be with her husband?

09:31.048 --> 09:32.441
Yeah, so?

09:34.574 --> 09:36.010
Don't start with me.

09:37.533 --> 09:38.839
Where is Trini?

09:38.882 --> 09:40.014
They're short-staffed
at the ICU.

09:40.057 --> 09:41.668
She's covering.
- Well, I need her.

09:41.711 --> 09:43.539
She's supposed to make
a house call with me.

09:43.583 --> 09:45.323
Oh. I'll go.

09:45.367 --> 09:46.890
Trini knows the patient,
you don't.

09:46.934 --> 09:48.370
What?

09:48.413 --> 09:49.763
Am I not the nurse
with more experience

09:49.806 --> 09:51.634
than anyone else down here?

09:51.678 --> 09:53.505
Sorry, Nurse Lockwood.
I'm sure you've seen it all.

09:53.549 --> 09:54.811
I'm grateful
for your assistance.

09:54.855 --> 09:56.857
Huh.

09:56.900 --> 09:59.207
Charge Nurse Lockwood.

09:59.250 --> 10:01.426
You're in a good mood.
- So are you.

10:01.470 --> 10:03.211
Mm-hmm.

10:03.254 --> 10:05.430
Dr. Hammer.
Good news, huh?

10:05.474 --> 10:08.782
- What's that?
- Your mom.

10:08.825 --> 10:10.044
I was just up
in the Psych Ward.

10:10.087 --> 10:11.959
I saw
that they're discharging her.

10:12.002 --> 10:13.438
Oh, right. Yeah.

10:18.182 --> 10:21.098
<i>[apprehensive music]</i>

10:21.142 --> 10:22.404
Kind of put them
in their separate corners,

10:22.447 --> 10:24.014
but other than that--
- My mother's here?

10:24.058 --> 10:25.059
Why didn't you tell me?

10:25.102 --> 10:27.365
- I couldn't.
- Why?

10:27.409 --> 10:30.368
Because she gave me
express orders not to.

10:30.412 --> 10:31.631
Well, this doesn't
make any sense.

10:31.674 --> 10:32.893
Did you commit her?

10:32.936 --> 10:34.503
I'm sorry, I can't
discuss that with you.

10:34.546 --> 10:35.678
She's my mother!

10:35.722 --> 10:36.940
Doesn't matter, Stevie.

10:36.984 --> 10:38.986
She's a patient here,
and she has rights.

10:39.029 --> 10:40.248
Okay, where is she?

10:40.291 --> 10:41.902
- Stevie--
- This is ridiculous.

10:41.945 --> 10:43.251
Come on.

10:43.294 --> 10:44.644
Are you really gonna
make me call security?

10:44.687 --> 10:51.651
<i>â™ª</i>

10:53.783 --> 10:56.743
Terri, good morning.

10:56.786 --> 10:59.223
Um.

10:59.267 --> 11:02.618
So Stevie found out
that you're here.

11:02.662 --> 11:03.967
How is she?

11:04.011 --> 11:05.926
She's a little confused.

11:05.969 --> 11:07.797
Right? She's--she's angry.

11:07.841 --> 11:10.800
She's--she's hurt.

11:10.844 --> 11:12.497
But, um...

11:12.541 --> 11:14.151
how would you like
to handle this?

11:14.195 --> 11:15.631
What--what would you like
me to tell her?

11:19.809 --> 11:21.158
Wait here, please.

11:22.682 --> 11:23.595
[phone buzzes]

11:27.077 --> 11:28.209
What's up?

11:29.776 --> 11:31.603
Nothing.

11:33.431 --> 11:34.563
Nice.

11:36.217 --> 11:38.436
Patient's
a financial planner.

11:38.480 --> 11:41.048
He's, uh, done well.
- Mm.

11:41.091 --> 11:43.398
- Dr. Halstead.
- Hey, Lenny.

11:44.573 --> 11:46.793
This is Maggie Lockwood,
our charge nurse.

11:46.836 --> 11:48.795
Hey.

11:48.838 --> 11:50.405
Ellis is ready.

11:52.450 --> 11:55.497
- Ellis, hi.
- Hey.

11:55.540 --> 11:57.455
Thank you for coming.
- Of course.

11:57.499 --> 11:59.631
I want you to meet my friend,
Maggie Lockwood.

12:01.155 --> 12:03.766
My pleasure, Maggie.

12:03.810 --> 12:05.202
Hi.

12:05.246 --> 12:11.208
<i>â™ª</i>

12:15.038 --> 12:18.389
When I was bathing him
this morning, he looked paler.

12:18.433 --> 12:20.348
I normally have
a healthy glow.

12:20.391 --> 12:21.610
Okay.

12:21.653 --> 12:23.046
Well, we're gonna need
to open the box

12:23.090 --> 12:24.178
so I can take a look.

12:24.221 --> 12:25.614
Can't be for long.

12:27.398 --> 12:29.531
Polio paralyzed
Ellis's diaphragm

12:29.574 --> 12:30.793
and intercostal muscles,

12:30.837 --> 12:32.621
so without the respirator,

12:32.664 --> 12:35.102
every breath requires
conscious effort.

12:35.145 --> 12:36.538
Polio.

12:36.581 --> 12:37.800
Contracted it
when he was five,

12:37.844 --> 12:39.454
a month
before the vaccine came out.

12:39.497 --> 12:40.716
Good timing, eh?

12:40.760 --> 12:41.804
Turning it off.

12:41.848 --> 12:44.111
<i>[machine powers down]</i>

12:44.154 --> 12:47.070
<i>[apprehensive music]</i>

12:47.114 --> 12:52.641
<i>â™ª</i>

12:52.684 --> 12:55.339
Those were my ward mates.

12:55.383 --> 12:56.993
Ellis has been
in the iron lung

12:57.037 --> 12:58.560
for 60 years.

12:58.603 --> 13:02.477
63.
But who's counting?

13:02.520 --> 13:04.174
He's also instructed me
more than once

13:04.218 --> 13:06.481
never to refer to him
as a polio victim.

13:07.351 --> 13:10.964
Life threw me a curveball,
that's all.

13:11.007 --> 13:13.140
I got lots to be thankful for.

13:13.183 --> 13:18.362
Found some friends,
work I enjoy,

13:18.406 --> 13:19.842
good docs like Halstead.

13:22.889 --> 13:25.065
Hey, how's your love life, huh?

13:25.108 --> 13:28.503
Last time we talked,
it wasn't so good.

13:28.546 --> 13:30.505
Hasn't gotten any better.

13:30.548 --> 13:32.463
Mm, I'm all ears.

13:32.507 --> 13:33.943
Nothing to tell.

13:33.987 --> 13:37.294
Ellis, I'm seeing
peripheral cyanosis

13:37.338 --> 13:39.166
and you're skin is cold.

13:39.209 --> 13:40.558
Maggie, pulse, please.

13:44.258 --> 13:46.129
Bradycardia.

13:46.173 --> 13:47.696
His HR's in the 50s.

13:47.739 --> 13:49.611
We need an EKG.
I brought one.

13:49.654 --> 13:50.786
You good
for a few more minutes?

13:50.830 --> 13:53.745
Oh, yeah.
I need the exercise.

13:55.225 --> 13:59.186
So, um, your mom
has given me permission

13:59.229 --> 14:01.492
to share her medical history
with you.

14:01.536 --> 14:04.191
- Well, that's big of her.
- Have a seat, please.

14:04.234 --> 14:05.279
I'm okay.

14:07.063 --> 14:10.197
So you're mom
admitted herself.

14:10.240 --> 14:11.589
She was very depressed

14:11.633 --> 14:13.765
and, uh, was worried
about self-harm.

14:13.809 --> 14:15.071
Oh, my God.

14:15.115 --> 14:17.900
She has been diagnosed
with bipolar disorder.

14:17.944 --> 14:19.510
All right?
Which has, of course,

14:19.554 --> 14:22.035
been exacerbated
by her alcohol abuse.

14:22.078 --> 14:24.907
But admitting herself
to the hospital,

14:24.951 --> 14:27.475
seeking help--
really good sign.

14:27.518 --> 14:29.651
And I have to say,
with, uh--

14:29.694 --> 14:30.826
with treatment, right?

14:30.870 --> 14:32.045
With therapy,
with medication, she's--

14:32.088 --> 14:34.699
I've been trying
to reach her for weeks.

14:34.743 --> 14:35.918
No answer.

14:35.962 --> 14:37.920
She just hasn't returned
any of my calls.

14:37.964 --> 14:41.750
I'm, um--
I'm moving back to Michigan,

14:41.793 --> 14:43.404
but I didn't know
if I should.

14:43.447 --> 14:44.840
You know, Stevie,

14:44.884 --> 14:46.929
I'm so sorry that you've had
to go through this.

14:46.973 --> 14:50.063
Yet you were just fine
keeping me in the dark.

14:52.979 --> 14:54.763
Look, if it's
any consolation,

14:54.806 --> 14:56.330
you're mom?

14:56.373 --> 14:59.594
She's doing very well.

14:59.637 --> 15:02.292
Yeah, okay.

15:02.336 --> 15:04.164
But did it have to mean
cutting me out of her life?

15:04.207 --> 15:08.820
<i>â™ª</i>

15:14.435 --> 15:16.785
So Doc, am I gonna live?

15:16.828 --> 15:18.569
Well, our heart rate's
hovering around 49,

15:18.613 --> 15:20.528
not quite the picture
of heart health.

15:20.571 --> 15:22.356
Any more good news?

15:22.399 --> 15:23.879
EKG also shows low voltage,

15:23.923 --> 15:25.402
and I wish your BP was higher.

15:25.446 --> 15:28.579
However, these alone don't
point to anything specific.

15:28.623 --> 15:30.320
- Blood work?
- Yeah.

15:30.364 --> 15:33.758
So Ellis, we gotta place a line
so we can collect your samples.

15:33.802 --> 15:35.064
Unfortunately, you know,

15:35.108 --> 15:36.283
the only place
we have access to

15:36.326 --> 15:37.327
is your neck.

15:39.503 --> 15:40.983
Gets better and better.

15:41.027 --> 15:42.767
Mr. Turner, I'm gonna
ask you to remain

15:42.811 --> 15:44.769
as still as possible.

15:44.813 --> 15:47.250
Uh-huh. And shut up.
I--I get it.

15:49.252 --> 15:50.688
And we're in.

15:57.608 --> 15:59.393
I know a private lab nearby.

15:59.436 --> 16:00.829
I'll have them run the tests.

16:00.872 --> 16:02.744
We'll get a quick turnaround.

16:02.787 --> 16:04.093
Should I be worried?

16:04.137 --> 16:05.138
Hey, whatever's causing
your symptoms,

16:05.181 --> 16:07.009
we'll deal with it.
- Okay.

16:11.753 --> 16:13.233
Sorry about before.

16:13.276 --> 16:16.584
I shouldn't have made that
crack about your love life.

16:16.627 --> 16:18.325
What's going on with you?

16:18.368 --> 16:19.979
I'll talk to you
about it later.

16:20.022 --> 16:22.068
You need to get to the lab.

16:25.462 --> 16:26.594
We won't know the size

16:26.637 --> 16:27.943
of the recipient's
abdominal cavity

16:27.987 --> 16:29.249
until we open her up.

16:29.292 --> 16:31.164
So we'll resect
the donor liver then

16:31.207 --> 16:32.513
according to the body weight ratio.

16:32.556 --> 16:34.384
Right, get as close
a match as possible.

16:34.428 --> 16:36.560
Good morning.

16:36.604 --> 16:37.953
How's everyone doing?

16:37.997 --> 16:39.694
We're all a little nervous.

16:39.737 --> 16:42.305
- Her most of all.
- Yeah.

16:42.349 --> 16:43.306
So how you feeling?

16:43.350 --> 16:44.699
Good. Ready to go.

16:44.742 --> 16:46.396
And how's our recipient?

16:46.440 --> 16:49.660
Stable, lightly sedated,
but no reason not to proceed.

16:49.704 --> 16:52.141
They're gonna make you
all well, honey.

16:52.185 --> 16:53.621
The techs are gonna
be in shortly

16:53.664 --> 16:55.971
to take your daughter
and you, Mr. Byers, to pre-op.

16:57.320 --> 16:58.669
I love you.

16:58.713 --> 17:02.978
<i>â™ª</i>

17:03.022 --> 17:05.894
So we'll see you guys
on the other side, yeah?

17:05.937 --> 17:07.896
You all right?
All right, I'll see you.

17:07.939 --> 17:10.464
Hey, Pamela? Pamela.

17:10.507 --> 17:11.900
Hey, look, I spoke with Avery,

17:11.943 --> 17:13.336
and I made it clear
you had no idea

17:13.380 --> 17:14.381
we'd gone out.

17:14.424 --> 17:15.556
You mean, so she
wouldn't think

17:15.599 --> 17:16.731
that her mom
was snaking her boyfriend?

17:16.774 --> 17:18.994
[sighs]

17:19.038 --> 17:21.910
- What a mess.
- I know, come on.

17:21.953 --> 17:23.520
I want to make things right.

17:23.564 --> 17:25.261
I want to make things right
between you and me.

17:27.307 --> 17:29.657
Look, I also told Avery
I had--I had feelings for you.

17:29.700 --> 17:31.311
Okay, stop.
Stop, stop, stop.

17:33.095 --> 17:34.227
I never should have let
myself get involved.

17:34.270 --> 17:36.925
You're a surgeon.
You're on my team.

17:36.968 --> 17:38.361
That's all.

17:38.405 --> 17:41.364
<i>[tense music]</i>

17:41.408 --> 17:45.977
<i>â™ª</i>

17:49.981 --> 17:52.201
Dr. Taylor, Dr. Shentu,
need you.

17:52.245 --> 17:53.637
O2 started dropping.

17:53.681 --> 17:56.466
I put her on a mask
at 10 liters.

17:56.510 --> 17:58.294
- [gasping]
- Need a chest x-ray.

17:58.338 --> 18:00.383
<i>[tense music]</i>

18:00.427 --> 18:02.777
I'm hearing a rub.

18:02.820 --> 18:04.431
Okay, clear.

18:05.432 --> 18:07.303
[x-ray beeps]

18:07.347 --> 18:08.478
Her heart shadow
looks a little fuzzy.

18:08.522 --> 18:11.002
- Ultrasound?
- Yeah.

18:11.046 --> 18:12.656
It's gonna be okay, Gia.

18:17.052 --> 18:19.272
Okay.

18:19.315 --> 18:20.664
Pericardial effusion.

18:20.708 --> 18:22.579
Why didn't your morning
work up catch it?

18:22.623 --> 18:24.146
Wasn't on CT,
but things change.

18:24.190 --> 18:26.757
Could be a blunt cardiac injury
from the crash.

18:26.801 --> 18:28.977
We need to perform
pericardiocentesis.

18:29.020 --> 18:30.326
Dr. Shentu, it's not
indicated at this time.

18:30.370 --> 18:31.414
She's not in tamponade.

18:31.458 --> 18:33.155
She's protecting her airway,

18:33.199 --> 18:35.723
her condition is not emergent.

18:35.766 --> 18:38.247
And with a non-emergent
invasive procedure,

18:38.291 --> 18:41.163
we need Gia's permission
before we can perform it.

18:41.207 --> 18:42.947
Like the Xyrem?

18:42.991 --> 18:45.080
[sighs]
Yes.

18:45.124 --> 18:47.082
Another new guideline.

18:47.126 --> 18:50.912
Well, let's hope she regains
consciousness soon.

18:50.955 --> 18:57.179
<i>â™ª</i>

18:57.223 --> 19:00.878
[machine beeping]

19:00.922 --> 19:03.403
Resected the left lateral
segment.

19:12.890 --> 19:17.286
Graft-to-recipient
weight ratio is 4.2%.

19:17.330 --> 19:19.027
All right,
resection complete.

19:19.070 --> 19:21.203
Go ahead and put that on ice
for Lily's transplant.

19:21.247 --> 19:23.553
Let's get ready to close.

19:23.597 --> 19:25.468
You're heart rate's
not getting any better.

19:27.383 --> 19:29.342
Same as your BP.

19:29.385 --> 19:32.736
- What are you not telling him?
- What?

19:32.780 --> 19:35.043
Halstead.
What are you not telling him?

19:36.697 --> 19:38.960
Come on, come on.
I'm in an iron lung.

19:39.003 --> 19:40.353
I'm allowed to be nosy.

19:45.140 --> 19:48.187
I had a biopsy.

19:48.230 --> 19:49.536
Cancer, maybe?

19:49.579 --> 19:51.538
<i>[pensive music]</i>

19:51.581 --> 19:54.584
And why didn't you tell him?

19:54.628 --> 19:56.760
I don't want
people worrying about me.

19:58.414 --> 20:00.938
Yeah, I get that.

20:00.982 --> 20:05.334
I'm not much
for pity parties, myself.

20:05.378 --> 20:06.509
No.

20:07.945 --> 20:13.516
So what are you going to do
if it's positive?

20:13.560 --> 20:15.475
I don't know.

20:15.518 --> 20:22.221
<i>â™ª</i>

20:22.264 --> 20:24.745
Depends on how serious it is.

20:24.788 --> 20:28.662
Chemo, radiation, surgery.

20:30.316 --> 20:32.318
I'd have to stop working.

20:33.971 --> 20:37.018
So how are you set
for retirement?

20:37.061 --> 20:38.585
[chuckles]

20:38.628 --> 20:40.543
I don't know.
I haven't thought about that.

20:40.587 --> 20:42.806
Yeah, but you should.

20:43.851 --> 20:45.679
So you want me to take a look
at your financials with you?

20:45.722 --> 20:48.377
- I can't ask you to do that.
- Why not?

20:48.421 --> 20:51.075
- Because you're my patient.
- Get your phone.

20:51.119 --> 20:52.773
Pull up your accounts
and email them to me,

20:52.816 --> 20:54.601
and we'll go over them
together.

20:56.037 --> 20:57.430
- Now?
- Yeah.

20:57.473 --> 20:59.083
[laughs]

20:59.127 --> 21:00.737
I don't believe
in putting things off.

21:00.781 --> 21:02.130
[laughs]

21:04.350 --> 21:06.700
[monitor beeping]

21:09.050 --> 21:11.400
Hi, Terrell.

21:11.444 --> 21:15.056
Hi, I am Dr. Archer,
this is Dr. Hammer.

21:15.099 --> 21:17.406
I was the surgeon who performed
a procedure on your forearm.

21:17.450 --> 21:20.322
[groans]
What happened?

21:20.366 --> 21:22.150
You were found
near Washington Park.

21:22.193 --> 21:23.456
You were passed out
and laying on your arm,

21:23.499 --> 21:24.761
which lead to a condition

21:24.805 --> 21:27.373
which needed
to be treated surgically.

21:27.416 --> 21:30.593
You're lucky Dr. Archer
was able to operate so quickly.

21:30.637 --> 21:32.421
It could have been
very serious.

21:34.380 --> 21:35.729
Does my wife know?

21:35.772 --> 21:38.122
Yeah, uh, she's here
in the PICU with your son.

21:39.515 --> 21:41.604
Yeah, she must be so mad.

21:41.648 --> 21:42.823
Do you want me
to have her come see you?

21:42.866 --> 21:45.391
No.

21:45.434 --> 21:47.044
No, please.
Not like this.

21:49.351 --> 21:50.874
Can I go home today?

21:50.918 --> 21:52.528
Well, I wouldn't
recommend it,

21:52.572 --> 21:55.183
but, uh, if you insist--
- I do.

21:56.532 --> 21:58.055
And, um--

21:58.099 --> 22:01.537
and then after I'm dressed,
I'll--I'll see her.

22:01.581 --> 22:02.973
All right, well,
you rest,

22:03.017 --> 22:05.672
and we'll make sure
you get out of here.

22:12.635 --> 22:14.463
Living arrangements all set.

22:14.507 --> 22:18.337
And a van is on the way
to pick you up.

22:18.380 --> 22:19.860
Thank you, Dr. Charles.

22:21.514 --> 22:22.819
You know, Terri,

22:22.863 --> 22:24.995
there's something
that I've been curious about.

22:25.039 --> 22:26.867
Yeah?

22:26.910 --> 22:29.609
When you checked yourself
into a hospital

22:29.652 --> 22:31.872
where you knew
that Stevie worked,

22:31.915 --> 22:34.091
you had to think
that eventually

22:34.135 --> 22:37.007
she was gonna find out
that you were here.

22:37.051 --> 22:38.182
I did.

22:39.619 --> 22:41.272
I--I wanted to be
near her,

22:41.316 --> 22:43.927
and I thought

22:43.971 --> 22:45.799
eventually I would want
to see her.

22:46.974 --> 22:47.975
But...

22:49.324 --> 22:51.370
The better I got,

22:51.413 --> 22:55.330
the more I felt I was
turning my life around,

22:55.374 --> 22:57.114
the less I wanted to see her.

22:57.158 --> 22:59.116
Does that sound terrible?

22:59.160 --> 23:00.683
No.

23:00.727 --> 23:02.598
I love my daughter.

23:02.642 --> 23:07.255
I--I do,
but she can be negative.

23:09.344 --> 23:10.998
Even if she doesn't say it,

23:11.041 --> 23:13.522
Stevie always thinks I'll fail.

23:13.566 --> 23:15.437
I know I've given her
plenty of reasons

23:15.481 --> 23:18.397
to think that, but--

23:18.440 --> 23:21.965
Not necessarily something
you need right now.

23:22.009 --> 23:23.663
No.

23:26.361 --> 23:28.319
<i>[tense music]</i>

23:28.363 --> 23:31.018
Ah, Dr. Shentu.

23:31.061 --> 23:32.411
You know, I heard
about your inability

23:32.454 --> 23:33.455
to treat your patient.

23:33.499 --> 23:35.631
But hey,
you stand by your rules.

23:35.675 --> 23:36.893
Somebody's gotta set
an example.

23:38.547 --> 23:40.854
Dr. Shentu?
Dr. Taylor needs you.

23:42.899 --> 23:44.379
I decided
to scan her heart again

23:44.423 --> 23:46.468
just to be sure, and look.

23:46.512 --> 23:47.948
You can see
the beginning stages of--

23:47.991 --> 23:50.080
Diastolic collapse
of the right ventricle.

23:50.124 --> 23:52.431
It's a sign of impending
cardiac tamponade.

23:52.474 --> 23:55.869
Congratulations,
her condition is now emergent.

23:55.912 --> 23:57.610
We can perform
the pericardiocentesis

23:57.653 --> 23:59.655
without consent.
Doris, bolus fluids.

23:59.699 --> 24:02.832
Add 125 milligrams
of solumedrol,

24:02.876 --> 24:05.008
and set up a pericardial tap.

24:05.052 --> 24:07.489
[monitor beeping]

24:07.533 --> 24:10.013
Heart rate 145,
BP 88/48.

24:10.057 --> 24:11.058
She's tanking.

24:11.101 --> 24:17.151
<i>â™ª</i>

24:17.194 --> 24:18.195
What do you think?

24:18.239 --> 24:19.240
Maybe this could
have been avoided?

24:27.422 --> 24:28.467
[knock at door]

24:29.816 --> 24:30.773
You mind?

24:30.817 --> 24:33.080
Come on in.

24:33.123 --> 24:37.824
Um, my mom...

24:37.867 --> 24:40.783
was, uh, was she bipolar
her whole life?

24:40.827 --> 24:42.959
The disorder does tend
to be genetic,

24:43.003 --> 24:44.787
but it doesn't usually present

24:44.831 --> 24:48.008
till late teens, early 20s.

24:48.051 --> 24:50.358
And the drinking? The drugs?

24:50.401 --> 24:54.014
Most likely an attempt
to self-medicate her condition.

24:54.057 --> 24:55.189
You know, problem is,

24:55.232 --> 24:57.496
it just invariably
makes it worse.

24:59.062 --> 25:01.108
I used to get
so angry at her.

25:02.413 --> 25:03.676
I thought she was
a drug addict.

25:03.719 --> 25:05.808
Happens all the time.

25:05.852 --> 25:07.070
You know, a, uh,

25:07.114 --> 25:10.117
a psychiatric illness
goes undiagnosed,

25:10.160 --> 25:13.163
people just assume
that it's an addiction issue.

25:13.207 --> 25:16.558
I thought the drinking,
drugs, were the cause,

25:16.602 --> 25:19.343
not the other way around.

25:19.387 --> 25:20.823
I mean, situations like that,

25:20.867 --> 25:22.564
they can, in a strange way,

25:22.608 --> 25:25.828
turn into kind of a--
a self-fulfilling prophecy.

25:25.872 --> 25:28.004
<i>[sentimental music]</i>

25:28.048 --> 25:30.964
Yeah, I'm always just, uh,

25:31.007 --> 25:33.488
waiting for her
to fall apart again.

25:33.532 --> 25:36.056
Well, of course you are,
because that's what she did

25:36.099 --> 25:39.842
over and over again
your entire life.

25:39.886 --> 25:43.585
Stevie, you gotta try
and take it easy on yourself.

25:43.629 --> 25:45.979
I think you should be
giving yourself credit for...

25:48.372 --> 25:50.200
Recognizing the importance
of seeing

25:50.244 --> 25:52.028
somebody that you love
in a new way.

25:52.072 --> 25:58.992
<i>â™ª</i>

26:00.602 --> 26:06.390
Okay, um, so if you do
have to stop working,

26:06.434 --> 26:08.610
you'll want
a risk-averse portfolio.

26:08.654 --> 26:11.047
So I'd--I'd get you
out of the mutual funds

26:11.091 --> 26:13.876
and put you in dividend stocks,

26:13.920 --> 26:16.009
and, uh, maybe an annuity.

26:16.052 --> 26:18.011
[phone buzzing]

26:18.054 --> 26:19.578
It's my doctor.

26:21.101 --> 26:23.190
Go ahead.

26:24.974 --> 26:26.976
Hello?

26:27.020 --> 26:29.022
Yeah.

26:29.065 --> 26:32.329
<i>[apprehensive music]</i>

26:32.373 --> 26:33.983
Thank you.

26:36.638 --> 26:38.335
Your biopsy?

26:38.379 --> 26:39.685
Yeah.

26:39.728 --> 26:41.295
Negative?

26:43.863 --> 26:46.300
Well, that's good news.

26:46.343 --> 26:48.258
Why aren't you jumping
up and down?

26:51.174 --> 26:53.133
This isn't
my first go-around.

26:54.743 --> 26:57.006
I've had cancer before.

26:57.050 --> 26:59.879
And I guess the--

26:59.922 --> 27:01.532
the possibility
of it coming back,

27:01.576 --> 27:03.709
it just--

27:03.752 --> 27:05.972
It will always be a worry.

27:08.322 --> 27:10.150
Can I give you a little advice?

27:10.193 --> 27:11.586
[chuckles]

27:14.894 --> 27:16.286
Okay.

27:16.330 --> 27:19.507
We all live
on a razor's edge.

27:19.550 --> 27:22.075
Everybody.

27:22.118 --> 27:24.643
Just some of us know it
more than others.

27:26.340 --> 27:29.560
In a way, we're the lucky ones.

27:30.997 --> 27:33.652
We have the good sense to...

27:35.044 --> 27:37.046
Cherish every moment.

27:38.482 --> 27:40.789
[sighs]

27:40.833 --> 27:43.009
So it looks like we'll
keep you in the mutual funds.

27:43.052 --> 27:45.707
[laughs]

27:46.795 --> 27:48.231
Okay.

27:48.275 --> 27:50.625
All right,
making the chevron incision.

27:50.669 --> 27:52.409
<i>[tense music]</i>

27:52.453 --> 27:54.237
Ready?

27:54.281 --> 27:57.719
[monitor beeping]

27:59.939 --> 28:02.811
So now you'll stay
in the ICU for observation,

28:02.855 --> 28:05.466
and tomorrow you'll be
transferred to Rheumatology.

28:05.509 --> 28:09.600
There they'll work up a plan
to address your fibromyalgia.

